com.neatnodes.algorithm

Class Species

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.neatnodes.algorithm.Species

  • class Species
extends java.lang.Object
    A class used to group together Genomes that are sufficiently similar to each other. Each Species has a representative Genome that potential members will have their similarity tested against.
    Author:
    Sam Griffin

    • Constructor Detail

      • Species

        Species(Genome representativeGenome,
        double maxFitness,
        int generationsWithoutImprovement,
        Configuration configuration)
        Creates a new empty Species. Because a Species is generally created as a continuation of a Species from the previous generation, arguments are available which allow the parameters of the previous generation's equivalent Species to be carried forward.
        Parameters:
        representativeGenome - The Genome that will be used to test other Genomes for their compatibility with this Species.
        maxFitness - The maximum fitness attained by a member of the Species so far.
        generationsWithoutImprovement - The number of generations since this Species last improved it's maximum fitness.
        configuration - A Configuration object containing the parameters required by the NEAT algorithm.

    • Method Detail

      • addGenome

        boolean addGenome(Genome g)
        Attempts to add a Genome to the Species. The Genome will only be added if it falls within the compatibility threshold specified by the Configuration object. This method will throw an exception if the Species has already been finalised.
        Parameters:
        g - The Genome to add.
        Returns:
        True if successful, or false if the Genome did not meet the criteria.

      • getGenomes

        java.util.ArrayList<Genome> getGenomes()
        Get the list of all Genomes in the Species.
        Returns:
        The list of Genomes.

      • calculateAverageFitness

        void calculateAverageFitness()
        Calculates the adjusted fitnesses for all Genomes in the species and sums them together to create the adjusted fitness sum specified by the NEAT algorithm (i.e. the average fitness across the whole Species). This value is used to determine how many offspring the Species will produce. Calling this method will finalise the Species, which means that no new Genomes can be added.

      • getAverageFitness

        double getAverageFitness()
        Get the average fitness (aka the adjusted fitness sum) of the Species. This method will throw an exception if it is called before the Species has been finalised.
        Returns:
        The average fitness.

      • getMaxFitness

        double getMaxFitness()
        Get the maximum fitness attained by any member of the Species.
        Returns:
        The maximum fitness.

      • getGenerationsWithoutImprovement

        int getGenerationsWithoutImprovement()
        Get the number of generations since this Species last improved it's maximum fitness.
        Returns:
        The number of generations without improvement.

      • isFinalised

        boolean isFinalised()
        Check if the Species has been finalised yet.
        Returns:
        True if the Species has been finalised.

      • produceOffspring

        Genome produceOffspring(boolean crossover,
                        InnovationManager iManager)
        Creates an offspring Genome bred from members of this Species. Mutations will be applied to the new Genome as specified by the NEAT algorithm. This method will throw an exception if it is called before the Species has been finalised.
        Parameters:
        crossover - If true, two random members will be bred with each other, otherwise a single member will be bred with itself.
        iManager - The InnovationManager to use when selecting innovation numbers as part of the breeding process.
        Returns:
        The new offspring Genome.

      • cull

        Genome cull()
        Remove the weakest 50% of Genomes in the Species and return the Genome with the highest fitness. If the fitness of that Genome exceeds the current maximum fitness of the Species, that becomes the new maximum fitness.
        Returns:
        The most fit Genome in the Species.
